the Greek town Hipponium, on the west coast of Bruttium, on the shores of the bay named aster it sinus Hipponiates or Vibonen- sis, now the guls of St Eufemia. Originally a colony of the Locri Epizephyrii, it was destroyed by Dionysius in Β. C. 389 but restored by the Carthaginians in B.C. 379, soon after which it sell into the hands of the Bruttii. Upon the close of the second Punic war, the Romans colonised it, and gave it the name of Vibo Valentia. Cicero speaks of it (Verr. 11 5 ἓ 40) as an illustre nobileque municipium, and Appian B. C. lv 3, as one of the most flourishing cities in Italy. Its position rendered it a convenient place to touch at in passing from or to Sicily. Thus we find Cicero in B.C. 44 proceeding a Vibone ad Veliam par- vulo navigio, and thence to Rhegium, Verr. 11 2 §99, cs. cp. ad Att. Brundisium] the modern Brindisi, a town in Calabria on the coast of the Adriatic, colonised by the Romans in Β. C. 244, was their chief naval station in those seas on account of the excellence of its harbour (Brun disin m pulcro praccinclum praepete portu Ennius Ann- V1 53).
